## The naive approach is using the inbuilt count() method in python, and removing (count-2) instances of the element.
## For example the array nums = [1,1,1,1,2,2,2,3,3], it will delete (count of 1 - 2) 1's, that is 4-2 = 2 ones, and so on.
## count() method in python returns the frequency of the element, if the frequency is less than 2 skip one place and go ahead if it's more than 2, delete (count-2) elements and then skip 2 places.
```
class Solution:
    def removeDuplicates(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        length = len(nums)
        if len(nums) < 2:
            return length
        i = 0
        while(i <=  length-1):
            count = nums.count(nums[i])
            if count > 2:
                for _ in range(i,i+count-2):
                    nums.pop(i)
                i += 2
                length -= (count-2)
            else:
                i += 1
	```
# Efficient 2-pointer approach
## This approach has a start and an end pointer which is 2 indices ahead of start, everytime nums[end] == nums[start], it deleted nums[end]. Once 1st element is done, start shifts to end, and end shifts to start+2.

```def  removeDuplicates(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        length = len(nums)
        if length < 2:
            return length
        start = 0
        end = start + 2

        while(end <= length-1):
            if nums[start+1] == nums[start]:
                if nums[end] > nums[start]:
                    start = end
                    end += 2
                else:
                    nums.pop(end)
                    length -= 1
            else:
                start += 1
                end += 1

